            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-04-14T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-04-14T02:00:00-05:00" n="286" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d286">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4–1449: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister-Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clark</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-04-14T15:00:00+08:00">April 14, 1949—3 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:37 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Cantel 212. Hsueh Yueh confirms that he and Kuangtung legislators will not accept
                    coalition either nationally or provincially, Cantel 211, repeated Nanking 186,
                    Shanghai 136, April 14, 3 p. m. They retain deep suspicion that Li Tsung-jen may
                    be led sell out [to] Communists and Hsueh Yueh says he has received direct word
                    from Peiping that Li Chi-shen, Fu Tso-yi and others who have succumbed to
                    Communist propaganda are much restricted in their activities and are
                    unhappy.</p>
                <p>Sent Department; repeated Nanking 187, Shanghai 137.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
